article.description: Orlando -- missing coach Dee Brown, who was with his wife as she gave birth to their third child -- snapped a three-game losing streak by rallying for a 79-71 overtime victory over the Indiana Fever on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Miracle work OT to beat Fever, end skid
article.linkText: Without coach Brown, Miracle end three-game skid
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- The Orlando Miracle delivered a big win without coach Dee Brown on the sidelines. Orlando -- missing Brown, who was with his wife as she gave birth to their third child -- snapped a three-game losing streak by rallying for a 79-71 overtime victory over the Indiana Fever on Wednesday night. "We just came out, executed Coach Brown's game plan and fought for the whole game,'' said assistant coach Vonn Read, who led the Miracle to the win. Shannon Johnson scored 12 of her 15 points after halftime while Brooke Wyckoff added a career-high 13 points and seven rebounds in a spot start. Adrienne Johnson added a season-high 12 points, all on 3-pointers. Her final 3 with 2:40 to go snapped a 68-all tie as the Miracle closed the game on an 11-3 run. "Once I hit a couple, my confidence grew,'' Adrienne Johnson said. "They had some breakdowns and I was able to take advantage of them.'' Katie Douglas had six of her 12 points in overtime for the Miracle (8-6). Tamika Catchings scored 24 points to lead Indiana (6-9), which lost for the fourth time in five games. Nadine Malcolm added 19, but missed a crucial free throw with 9.7 seconds left in regulation. After Malcolm's miss, Shannon Johnson took the rebound, charged upcourt and converted an untouched layup to tie it at 63 with 3.1 seconds left. Aiding her full-speed drive was a quick look to Adrienne Johnson, who was spotted up beyond the arc, to freeze the defense. "When they missed the free throw, it gave us a lot of running room because they were trying for a rebound,'' Shannon Johnson said. Indiana, behind Catchings, took a 14-point advantage with 11:14 left in the second half. She hit two 3-pointers as the Fever scored 12 unanswered points for a 49-35 lead. Catchings, who scored 17 points after the break, set a WNBA record by making six 3-pointers without a miss. She fell one 3-pointer shy of tying the league record for 3s in a game. But within five minutes, Orlando closed within three as Wyckoff, Shannon Johnson and Adrienne Johnson all hit 3s and the Miracle cut the deficit to 52-49 with six minutes remaining. "I thought we made some poor decisions down the stretch, and Orlando was able to capitalize,'' said Indiana coach Nell Fortner, who refused to allow the media to speak with the team. "They hit some big shots, and it caused the momentum of the game to change.''

Game notes
Orlando also was without power forward Taj McWilliams-Franklin, who didn't suit up because of the flu. Wyckoff started in her place. ... Indiana has played eight of its last 10 games on the road, but begins an eight-game homestand Saturday.
